Abstract = {{Polycentric theory, as applied to sustainability policy adoption,
   contends that municipalities will act independently to provide public
   services that protect the environment. Our multilevel regression
   analysis of survey responses from 1,497 municipalities across the United
   States challenges that notion. We find that internal drivers of
   municipal action are insufficient. Lower policy adoption is explained by
   capacity constraints. More policy making occurs in states with a
   multilevel governance framework supportive of local sustainability
   action. Contrary to Fischel's homevoter hypothesis, we find large cities
   and rural areas show higher levels of adoption than suburbs (possibly
