Year = {{2014}},
Volume = {{8}},
Number = {{14}},
Pages = {{1143-1153}},
Month = {{NOV 18}},
Abstract = {{The tremendous growth of low power wireless technologies oriented to
   smart city applications has conduced to evaluate the propagation aspects
   under typical communication scenarios in urban environments where in
   contrast to cellular technologies the transmitter and or the receiver
   antenna can be deployed at different heights near ground. Thus, the
   authors introduce a unified empiric parametrised propagation model with
   validated parameters from the measurements to study the propagation
   characteristics in near-ground scenarios. The proposed model considers
   the antenna's height as well as external power losses because of objects
   that may block the line-of-sight to the receiver. The main results of
   this research demonstrate that in near-ground wireless links, the
   wireless range is severely reduced because of diffraction caused by
   ground. However, in scenarios where the receiver is always higher than
   the transmitter the diffraction is null and the path loss slope is less
   than free space, with the consequence of a considerably higher wireless
   range. The propagation model presented here is a valuable tool for
   network planning where typical cellular propagation models might not be
   appropriate.}},
