Number = {{6}},
Pages = {{136-141}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{Cities are growing steadily, and the process of urbanization is a common
   trend in the world. Although cities are getting bigger, they are not
   necessarily getting better. With the aim to provide citizens with a
   better place to live, a new concept of a city was born: the smart city.
   The real meaning of smart city is not strictly defined, but it has
   gained much attention, and many cities are taking action in order to be
   considered ``smart.{''} These smart cities, founded on the use of
   information and communication technologies, aim at tackling many local
   problems, from local economy and transportation to quality of life and
   e-governance. Although technology helps to solve many of these local
   problems, their ability to gather unprecedented amounts of information
   could endanger the privacy of citizens. In this article we identify a
   number of privacy breaches that can appear within the context of smart
   cities and their services. We leverage some concepts of previously
   defined privacy models and define the concept of citizens' privacy as a
   model with five dimensions: identity privacy, query privacy, location
   privacy, footprint privacy and owner privacy. By means of several
   examples of smart city services, we define each privacy dimension and
   show how existing privacy enhancing technologies could be used to
   preserve citizens' privacy.}},
